10 Section 2. KRS 156.101 is amended to read as follows:
11 (1) The purpose of this section is to encourage and require the maintenance and
12 development of effective instructional leadership in the public schools of the
13 Commonwealth and to recognize that principals, with the assistance of assistant
14 principals, supervisors of instruction, guidance counselors, and directors of special
15 education, have the primary responsibility for instructional leadership in the schools
16 to which they are assigned.
17 (2) As used in[For the purpose of] this section, "instructional leader" means[shall be
18 defined as] an employee of the public schools of the Commonwealth employed as a
19 principal, assistant principal, supervisor of instruction, guidance counselor, director
20 of special education, or other administrative position deemed by the Education
21 Professional Standards Board to require an administrative certificate.
22 (3) In order to carry out the purpose of this section, the Kentucky Board of Education
23 shall establish a statewide program to improve and maintain the quality[ and
24 effectiveness] of effective instructional leadership in the public schools of the
25 Commonwealth.
26 (4) The effective instructional leadership[instructional leader improvement] program
27 shall contain the following provisions:
Page 4 of 35
SB000490.100 - 1215 - XXXX 4/14/2026 1:59 PM Vetoed and Overridden

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS SB 4/VO
1 (a) Each instructional leader employed by the public schools of the
2 Commonwealth shall participate in a continuing intensive training program
3 designed especially for instructional leaders;
4 (b) Each instructional leader shall annually complete an intensive training
5 program approved by the Kentucky Board of Education to include no fewer
6 than twenty-one (21) participant hours of instruction. Hours completed by
7 participants in the principal leadership development practicum under
8 Section 1 of this Act may be substituted to satisfy this requirement;
9 (c) The Kentucky Board of Education shall prescribe specific criteria for the
10 training program. The Kentucky Department of Education may contract for
11 specific training with qualified agencies or institutions or approve programs
12 offered by training providers, including local district training programs,
13 except that the department shall ensure the requirements of paragraph (d) of
14 this subsection are met; and
15 (d) Annually, each local district superintendent shall report to the Kentucky
16 Department of Education any instructional leader who fails to complete the
17 training requirements of paragraph (b) of this subsection and shall place the
18 leader on probation for one (1) year. The Department of Education shall
19 verify completion of the required training. If the required training for the prior
20 year and the current year is not completed during the probationary period, the
21 Department of Education shall forward the information to the Education
22 Professional Standards Board, which shall revoke the instructional leader's
23 certificate.
24 (5) The Kentucky Department of Education shall ensure that training options in human
25 resource management and conflict resolution techniques are available to education
26 leaders throughout the state.
27 (6) This section shall be known as the ["]Effective Instructional Leadership Act.["]
